The paper focuses on the problem of controlling physically simulated humanoids, which falls under the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The proposed motor architecture involves neural networks, which suggests a connection to machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of visual input for controlling the humanoid, which could relate to computer vision (cs.CV). Finally, the paper discusses the training of controllers, which could be relevant to the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category.
